<TITLE> Stocks perk up on DBH's debut </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, April 24 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka stocks closed higher Thursday, driven by a hike in the prices of Delta BRAC Housing. The company's primary shares ended almost 15 times higher than its face value after debuting on the capital market. Turnover and trading volume on the country's twin bourses witnessed a fall from the previous day. "Investors sold off oil shares and major issues in banks, pharmaceuticals, mutual funds, cement and leather," an official with brokerage house Latif Securities told bdnews24.com. Power companies however enjoyed a limited buying spree, the official added. Market watchers termed the day's trading satisfactory, saying that the prices of DBH pushed the indices up. "The trading pattern of the last couple of days continued today. A hike in DBH share prices led the indices to close this much higher," said chief executive of Dhaka Stock Exchange Salahuddin Ahmed. The benchmark DGEN or general index rose sharply on the opening bell and remained stable afterwards only to fall in midday trade. It however rose toward the end to finish 26.02 points, or 0.85 percent higher at 3079.34. The DSI or all-share price index ended on 2599.60, rising 18.75 points, or 0.72 percent from the previous day. The bourse's blue-chip DSE-20 also gained 25.95 points, or 1.09 percent, to close at 2394.87. Turnover slipped to Tk 3.02 billion from Wednesday's Tk 3.14 billion, with 15,454,561 shares changing hands. Of the traded issues, 88 advanced, 158 declined and six remained unchanged. Delta BRAC Housing topped the turnover board on its debut, finishing at Tk 1563.25. Square Pharma followed it to end on Tk 4566, up 0.14 percent after Wednesday's losses while AB Bank also advanced 0.95 percent to Tk 3683.25. BATBC ended on Tk 170.20, rising 12.26 percent from the previous day's closing. UCBL eroded Wednesday's gains to close at Tk 4899.25, down 0.08 percent. Among the other scrips on the turnover board, state-owned Jamuna Oil, ACI, Heidelberg Cement and IFIC Bank declined after investors locked in profits. DESCO rose on buying pressure. Indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended higher, paced by gains in miscellaneous, ceramics, textile and insurance sector. The CSCX or selective categories index rose 10.46 points or 0.18 percent to 5532.85 while the CASPI or all-share price index ended on 8571.61, up 18.03 points or 0.21 percent. The CSE-30 blue-chip index surged 59.05 points or 0.79 percent to close at 7455.03. Turnover on the port city's bourse fell to Tk 399.40 million from Tk 446.17 million the previous day from 2,571,708 traded shares. bdn
